    <div class="article-body" data-pp-location="article body" >

        
                    <div class="article-body__top-notes" data-pp-location="top-note">
                

                                                
            <div class="article-body__note article-body__note--newsletter" id="newsletter-txt-note">
                <p>ProPublica is a nonprofit newsroom that investigates abuses of power. <a href="https://www.propublica.org/newsletters/dispatches?source=www.propublica.org&amp;placement=top-note&amp;region=national">Sign up for Dispatches</a>, a newsletter that spotlights wrongdoing around the country, to receive our stories in your inbox every week.</p>

            </div>

                

            </div><!-- end .article-body__top-notes -->
        
        




                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="3.0">Flint, Michigan, is less than 70 miles from the Great Lakes, the most abundant fresh water on the face of the planet. It’s laced with creeks and a broad river that bears its name. Yet in 2014, Flint’s drinking water became a threat — not because of scarcity, or a natural disaster, or even a familiar tale of corporate pollution.</p>
        
    
